EACH COUNT:  Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
All court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA);

-  No Cash Bail Posted in this matter  
-  Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. Defendant Kimberly Marie Meyer in court with attorney Kevin Michael Gaertner.  Ronald Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk  PSI reviewed and corrections made.  
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.


As to Count 1:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  9 YEARS with 220 days credit CONCURRENT to Count 2; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4.5 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 4.5 YEARS.
As to Count 2:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  9 YEARS CONCURRENT  to Count 3; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4.5 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 4.5 YEARS.
As to Count 3:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  9 YEARS CONCURRENT  to Count 4; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4.5 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 4.5 YEARS.
As to Count 4:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  9 YEARS; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4.5 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 4.5 YEARS.
These sentences are CONSECUTIVE to any other sentence.

Court finds defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program and the WI Substance Abuse program after serving 3.5 years of incarceration.
  Conditions of Extended Supervision:
- No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
- Cooperate with the Probation Department
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- Absolute/maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs.
- No possession or use of alcohol, drugs or drug paraphenalia.
- seek and maintain full time employment
- Random urine screens.
- No contact with victims and co-actors
- Provide a DNA sample.
- Court orders no other specific programming conditions.  Defendant must complete a risk and needs assessment with DOC and comply with case plan goals related to prioritized need areas so identified.

Defendant Kimberly Marie Meyer in court with attorney Kevin Michael Gaertner.  Defendant Kimberly Marie Meyer in custody.  Ronald Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk  As to all Counts:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum, elements and jury instructions, received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon she may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until her civil rights are restored.
Defendant is ordered to provide a DNA sample.
Court REMANDS the defendant.  Case is adjourned for sentencing in Branch 19.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for October 8, 2015 at 01:30 pm.
